). Other species of the recent 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lacepede" authorityYear="1802" box="[454,604,223,248]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Ostorhinchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="33" pageNumber="184" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[454,604,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">Ostorhinchus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were divided into four lineages, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lacepede" authorityYear="1802" box="[972,1122,223,248]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Ostorhinchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="33" pageNumber="184" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[972,1122,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">Ostorhinchus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-1, 2, 3 and 4. They were all placed far from the clade XII. Except for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lacepede" authorityYear="1802" box="[643,793,260,285]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Ostorhinchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="33" pageNumber="184" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[643,793,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">Ostorhinchus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-3 (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bleeker" baseAuthorityYear="1855" box="[837,1065,260,285]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Ostorhinchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="33" pageNumber="184" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="margaritophorus">
<emphasis box="[837,1065,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">O. margaritophorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), monophyly between this tribe (clade XII) and each of the remaining lineages was rejected by AU tests (H07, 08 and 
<quantity box="[1120,1176,295,320]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.794" pageId="33" pageNumber="184" unit="in" value="11.0">11 in</quantity>
<tableCitation box="[1183,1267,295,320]" captionStart="TABLE 6" captionStartId="14.[147,235,642,665]" captionTargetId="graphics-45@14.[131,1870,682,1530]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="TABLE 6. Statistical likelihood-based AU tests between unconstrained and constrained trees." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/16E9AFE381160B1DFF7CC4EAFBDFD4E2" pageId="33" pageNumber="184" tableUuid="16E9AFE381160B1DFF7CC4EAFBDFD4E2">Table 6</tableCitation>
). Although the bootstrap values supporting the clade XII were not so high (&lt;50%) both in the ML (
<figureCitation box="[1096,1163,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1809,1831]" captionTargetBox="[292,1276,196,1779]" captionTargetId="figure-147@15.[292,1289,193,1783]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 2. Phylogenetic tree from the partitioned maximum-likelihood (ML) analysis. Numbers besides internal branches indicate bootstrap probabilities (BPs) from 1000 replicates (only those of&gt; 50% shown). Species names of recent Ostorhinchus [we included here Apogonichthyoides melas as a possible Ostorhinchus, following Mabuchi et al. (2006)] were blue, those of Apogon sensu lato [genus Apogon in Fraser (1972)] excepting the Ostorhinchus red, and those of genus Rhabdamia in Fraser (1972) green. The names of the twelve major clades (clades I to XII) within the Apogoninae were indicated on the left of the corresponding clades. Four species, which phylogenetic positions were largely different among the ML, Bayesian (BA: Fig. 3), and most parsimonious (MP: Figs. 4 and 5) tress, were indicated by arrows with asterisks." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4928551" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4928551/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) and MP (
<figureCitation box="[1281,1358,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1870,1892]" captionTargetBox="[375,1230,199,1845]" captionTargetId="figure-115@17.[344,1242,193,1849]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 4. Strict consensus tree of two of the five most parsimonious (MP) trees (MP tree-A). Numbers besides internal branches indicate bootstrap probabilities (BPs) from 1000 replicates (only those of&gt; 50% shown). Topological incongruity between the two MP trees denoted by an arrowhead. Four species, which phylogenetic positions were largely different among the ML (Fig. 2), BA (Fig. 3), and MP (Figs. 4 and 5) tress, were indicated by arrows with asterisks. Species names were colored as in Figure 2. The names of the twelve clades were indicated as in Figure 2." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4928559" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4928559/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">Figs. 4</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation box="[1413,1427,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1881,1903]" captionTargetBox="[375,1230,199,1856]" captionTargetId="figure-103@18.[344,1242,193,1860]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 5. Strict consensus tree of the remaining three of the five most parsimonious (MP) trees (MP tree-B). Topological incongruities between the three MP trees denoted by arrowheads. Four species, which phylogenetic positions were largely different among the ML (Fig. 2), BA (Fig. 3), and MP (Figs. 4 and 5) tress, were indicated by arrows with asterisks. This tree was largely different from the MP tree-A (Fig. 4) in the positions of Pterapogon kauderni and Vincentia novaehollandiae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4928561" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4928561/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">5</figureCitation>
) trees (
<tableCitation box="[219,307,367,392]" captionStart="TABLE 4" captionStartId="13.[147,237,496,519]" captionTargetId="graphics-79@13.[131,1887,567,1140]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="TABLE 4. Major clades reproduced in ML, BA and MP analyses with its support values [bootstrap probabilities (BPs) for ML and MP analyses, Bayesian posterior probabilities (PPs) for BA analysis], genera included, and correspondence to the tribes that were morphologically defined in this study." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/16E9AFE381150B1EFF7CC798F981D45D" pageId="33" pageNumber="184" tableUuid="16E9AFE381150B1EFF7CC798F981D45D">Table 4</tableCitation>
), and further the clade was divided into two separate clades in the BA tree (
<figureCitation box="[1175,1244,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1890,1912]" captionTargetBox="[251,1313,199,1857]" captionTargetId="figure-109@16.[251,1343,193,1865]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 3. Phylogenetic tree (50% majority-rule consensus tree) from the partitioned Bayesian (BA) analysis. Numbers besides internal branches indicate Bayesian posterior probabilities (PPs: shown as percentages, only those of&gt; 50% shown). Species names were colored as in Figure 2. The names of the twelve major clades were indicated as in Figure 2. Four species, which phylogenetic positions were largely different among the ML (Fig. 2), BA (Fig. 3), and most parsimonious (MP: Figs. 4 and 5) tress, were indicated by arrows with asterisks." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4928553" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4928553/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
), we are treating this group as a single genus, based on the typical color pattern (stripes on body and/or head) shared by most of the included species. This group corresponds to the &quot;striped group&quot; of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lacepede" authorityYear="1802" box="[908,1058,439,464]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Ostorhinchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="33" pageNumber="184" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[908,1058,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">Ostorhinchus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authority="III" authorityName="III" box="[1075,1263,439,464]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Ostorhinchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="33" pageNumber="184" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1075,1225,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">Ostorhinchus</emphasis>
III
</taxonomicName>
) in 
<bibRefCitation author="Mabuchi, K. &amp; Okuda, N. &amp; Nishida, M." pageId="33" pageNumber="184" pagination="90 - 99" refId="ref34639" refString="Mabuchi, K., Okuda, N. &amp; Nishida, M. (2006) Molecular phylogeny and stripe pattern evolution in the cardinalfish genus Apogon. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 38, 90 - 99. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2005.05.003" type="journal article" year="2006">
Mabuchi 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">et al.</emphasis>
(2006)
</bibRefCitation>
. One of the other recent 
<taxonomicName box="[539,689,476,501]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Ostorhinchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="33" pageNumber="184" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[539,689,476,501]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">Ostorhinchus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lineages, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bleeker" baseAuthorityYear="1855" box="[801,1025,476,501]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Ostorhinchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="33" pageNumber="184" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="margaritophorus">
<emphasis box="[801,1025,476,501]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">O. margaritophorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, has long stripes, short bars between two long stripes on body and fused hypurals 1+2. Phylogenetic position of this species remains unsettled in the molecular trees (
<tableCitation box="[340,427,548,573]" captionStart="TABLE 5" captionStartId="13.[147,237,1246,1269]" captionTargetId="graphics-403@13.[131,1893,1317,1621]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="TABLE 5. Phylogenetic positions (sister clades or species) of four apogoninae species in the ML (Fig. 2), BA (Fig. 3) and MP (Figs. 4 and 5) trees. These species were included in none of the 12 major clades summarized in Table 4." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/16E9AFE381150B1EFF7CC2B6FCC3D368" pageId="33" pageNumber="184" tableUuid="16E9AFE381150B1EFF7CC2B6FCC3D368">Table 5</tableCitation>
), but monophyly between this species and the members of this tribe was not rejected by AU test (H01 in 
<tableCitation box="[349,437,583,608]" captionStart="TABLE 6" captionStartId="14.[147,235,642,665]" captionTargetId="graphics-45@14.[131,1870,682,1530]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="TABLE 6. Statistical likelihood-based AU tests between unconstrained and constrained trees." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/16E9AFE381160B1DFF7CC4EAFBDFD4E2" pageId="33" pageNumber="184" tableUuid="16E9AFE381160B1DFF7CC4EAFBDFD4E2">Table 6</tableCitation>
). Based on its featured color pattern, we tentatively included this species in this tribe. 
<taxonomicName box="[151,482,620,645]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="33" pageNumber="184" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="parvula" subGenus="Brephamia">
<emphasis box="[151,238,620,643]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">Apogon</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[255,379,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">Brephamia</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[395,482,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">parvula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a very similar species within this tribe. It is 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Allen Kuiter &amp; Randall" baseAuthorityYear="1994" box="[1030,1259,620,645]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Ostorhinchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="33" pageNumber="184" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="neotes">
<emphasis box="[1030,1259,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">Ostorhinchus neotes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Although they were not sister to each other in the molecular trees, their monophyly was not rejected by AU test (H 
<quantity box="[1273,1330,655,680]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.048" pageId="33" pageNumber="184" unit="in" value="12.0">12 in</quantity>
<tableCitation box="[1337,1422,655,680]" captionStart="TABLE 6" captionStartId="14.[147,235,642,665]" captionTargetId="graphics-45@14.[131,1870,682,1530]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="TABLE 6. Statistical likelihood-based AU tests between unconstrained and constrained trees." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/16E9AFE381160B1DFF7CC4EAFBDFD4E2" pageId="33" pageNumber="184" tableUuid="16E9AFE381160B1DFF7CC4EAFBDFD4E2">Table 6</tableCitation>
). While recognition of 
<taxonomicName authority="Jordan" authorityName="Jordan" box="[389,594,692,717]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Brephamia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="33" pageNumber="184" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[389,513,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">Brephamia</emphasis>
Jordan
</taxonomicName>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="Jordan, D. S. &amp; Jordan, E. K." box="[628,892,692,717]" pageId="33" pageNumber="184" pagination="1 - 92" refId="ref34008" refString="Jordan, D. S. &amp; Jordan, E. K. (1922) A list of the fishes of Hawaii, with notes and descriptions of new species. Memoires of the Carnegie Museum, 10 (1), 1 - 92, Pls. 1 - 4. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 46678" type="journal article" year="1922">
<collectingCountry box="[628,703,692,717]" name="Jordan" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">Jordan</collectingCountry>
&amp; 
<collectingCountry box="[737,812,692,717]" name="Jordan" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">Jordan</collectingCountry>
(1922)
</bibRefCitation>
as a subgenus or genus needs further evaluation, we synonymized it under the restricted 
<taxonomicName box="[609,759,727,752]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Ostorhinchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="33" pageNumber="184" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[609,759,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">Ostorhinchus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for the present. Likely synapomorphies may include color pattern groupings, probably at the subgenus level. At the genus level, with the exception of the loss of tiny first dorsal-fin spines, all species have 7 visible first dorsal spines, a serrated preopercular edge and most have blackish stomachs and intestines.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1437,151,968]" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">
There are two available names (
<taxonomicName authority="Whitley 1929" authorityName="Whitley" authorityYear="1929" box="[560,888,871,896]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Gronovichthys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="33" pageNumber="184" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[560,724,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">Gronovichthys</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Whitley, G. P." box="[731,888,871,896]" pageId="33" pageNumber="184" refId="ref36488" refString="Whitley, G. P. (1929) Names of fishes in Meuschen's index to the &quot; Zoophylacium Gronovianum. &quot;. Records of the Australian" type="book" year="1929">Whitley 1929</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName authority="Whitley 1930" authorityName="Whitley" authorityYear="1930" box="[900,1160,871,896]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Lovamia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="33" pageNumber="184" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[900,998,872,895]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="184">Lovamia</emphasis>
Whitley 1930
</taxonomicName>
) which could be used in the future. There are at least 93 species in the group. We have sampled 31 species. Whitley (1959) first used the present name at family level Ostorhinchidae. The name appeared once. We use the name at the tribal level.
</paragraph>
